        of the alphabet.  Each letter being the name of a child; each
        child is shown in the picture and described in the
        accompanying rhyme.  Under "L," for instance, there is a
        picture of a small boy turning a hand organ with a monkey
        beside him:
        <lg><l>Luigi's father is so kind</l><l>He often lets Luigi grind,</l><l>Or pass the monkey's cup of tin</l><l>And count the pennies that fall in</l></lg></p></note><pb facs="page_image3" type="signature"/><note>Bertha E. Mahony</note><pb facs="page_image4"/><pb facs="page_image5"/><note>1st Edition with 2 orig drawings by Rachel Field presented to BMM $2500.</note><pb facs="page_image6"/><note>Ex Libris <lb/>Bertha Mahony Miller <lb/> 1882-1969</note><pb facs="page_image7"/><note>An Alphabet</note><pb facs="page_image8"/><pb facs="page_image9"/><titlePage><docTitle><titlePart>AN ALPHABET FOR BOYS AND GIRLS</titlePart></docTitle><docAuthor>RACHEL FIELD</docAuthor><docImprint><pubPlace>Garden City New York</pubPlace><publisher>Doubleday, Page &amp; Company</publisher><date>1926</date></docImprint></titlePage><pb facs="page_image10"/><div type="copyright"><bibl>COPYRIGHT, <date>1926, </date>BY <publisher>DOUBLEDAY, PAGE &amp; COMPANY. </publisher>
      ALL RIGHTS RESERVED. PRINTED IN THE UNITED STATES AT THE COUNTRY LIFE PRESS, GARDEN CITY, N.Y. <lb/> FIRST EDITION</bibl></div><pb facs="page_image11"/><div><ab>An Alphabet</ab></div></front><body><pb facs="page_image12"/><div><head>A<lb/>IS FOR<lb/>ANN</head><lg><l>ANN is the clever child who can</l><l>Make pancakes fry in a frying <lb/> pan.</l><l>Yet she's not proud as I should <lb/>be</l><l>If I were such a cook as she!</l></lg></div><pb facs="page_image13"/>
